 <methods> <methodStep> <description> <section> <title>Amazon Transitional Forest Leaf Traits</title>
 <para>Leaves were subsampled for measurements by randomly selecting 40 leaves (eight from each of the five individual samples) from each of the 17 tree species. Individual dry leaf mass was recorded to the nearest 0.01 g. Maximum leaf curl (height above a flat surface) was measured to the nearest millimeter with a standard ruler. Leaf thickness was measured at the edge of each leaf to the nearest 0.001 g, between primary veins, using an electronic caliper. Using a flatbed scanner, digital images were obtained for all leaves which were then used in the image processing program ImageJ (Rasband, 2012) to measure length (including petiole), width (at the widest point), perimeter, and surface area. Leaf volume was calculated by multiplying the leaf thickness by the one-sided surface area. Surface area to volume ratio was then found by summing edge thickness and two-sided surface area and then dividing by volume. Specific leaf area was calculated by dividing the leaf’s one-sided surface area by its dry mass.</para>
 </section>
 </description>
 </methodStep>
 <sampling> <studyExtent> <description> <para>The experimental forests are found within the region’s remaining transitional forest formation. Soils are Oxisols with a water table at 12-15 m. depth and no impeding layers. One experimental plot (150 ha.) with three treatment plots (50 ha. each) were established in order to conduct experimental burns. The treatment plots include a control plot, a plot burned once in 3 years, and a plot burned three times in 3 years. Between July 2004 and February 2006, average dry-season temperature was 25°C and average relative humidity was 66%. For the same time period, mean precipitation was 1738 mm yr -1.</para>
 </description>
 </studyExtent>
 <samplingDescription> <para>Leaf litter was collected from 17 of the most common species, which represent 70.62% of the Importance Value Index (IVI) in this forest plot. Litter samples were collected only from the control plot so that any effects of previous burns were eliminated. Samples for each of the 17 species were taken directly from the forest floor beneath randomly selected individuals, with five separate 50 g (dry weight) samples taken for each species. When sampling, any debris or leaves from adjacent species were excluded, therefore isolating the flammability characteristics specific only to that species. After drying, 15 g (± 0.08 g) subsamples were removed for burning experiments and the residual litter was held and subsampled for later leaf measurements.</para>
 </samplingDescription>
 </sampling>
